Welcom Page (pretty typical)\Our staff is dedicated to the goal of facilitating student growth through the development and mastery of academic competencies, positive self-concepts, critical thinking and effective communication skills, as well as leadership and decision-making skills.\\

Mission Statement:\To prepare students to become productive, well-informed, and responsible members of society.\Stromburg High School provides a flexible and varied curriculum that meets the intellectual, social, physical, cultural, technological, and career needs of its students. We are pleased to be able to share information about the many opportunities offered within our school and departments. \Through cooperative efforts between our staff and the community, we support students' learning and growth both now and in the future.\

Instruction Page:\Instructional Goals and objectives basic and not well-defined\Where's technology? 21st century skills? \Coimmunication skills are there, but implicit\\Curriculum is supposedly common and ongoing.\\Talking the talk on SWD and G/T students, but another page indicates there actually is no gifted program. Are they appropriately identifying G/T students?\\Diploma requirement seem to mirror their state's reauirements\\Discipline statement, but the data indicates that there are BIG increases in key areas.\\School Accountability for Student Learning:\HA! What is said (Student performance goals in reading and mathematics must, at a minimum, meet adequate yearly progress (AYP), as defined by No Child Left Behind (NCLB) Act, 2001. Individual high schools and the District must achieve school graduation rate goals of at least 73% in 2004 and 85% in 2014 for students in all identified groups. ) and what is happening are two different things. \\

At $2,000 per year per school, it's a good bargain if they use it. Of course, this faculty is filled with technophobes.\\Some of the existing areas could possibly be shaved a tiny bit ( subs? Standardized test scores for current sophomores ( from end of ninth and after the first term of 10th) show a statistically significant difference in LA ( low 50s) as compared with the other core areas, art & music, all of which are in the 60%-70% range.\\The curious thing to me is how can the students be doing so much better in science and social studies if they do so poorly in reading and writng. How are the students assessed in those areas?\\In any case, the scores need to be raised all around - 70% means that 30% aren't making it.

Stromburg teachers are coaches, advisors to student groups, committee members, and mentors to newer teachers. Currently, almost 60% of teachers are involved in some form of leadership.\\A broad-based committee of teachers, administrators, students, and parents has been working to design and implement the Literacy Improvement Focus (LIF).\\Teachers also serve as faculty representatives on the Technology Committee, Professional Development Committee, and Child Study Team.

Established school hours are 7:30 a.m. to 3:05 p.m., Monday through Friday.

Stromburg High School wants all new teachers to feel comfortable in both the school and their classrooms; therefore, we have established a mentoring program that relies upon the guidance and knowledge of its many veteran teachers. \\Beginning this year, teachers in their first year of teaching will be assigned to a mentor teacher, who is a more experienced teacher in their particular content area. Mentor Teams will meet once a month after school. The goals of this program are to help new teachers in: 1) curriculum implementation and classroom management, 2) integrating the Literacy Improvement Focus into their unit goals, 3) developing coherent lessons that address national standards in their content area, 4) adjusting to the profession of teaching. \\At the first meeting, the mentor's mission is to get the new teacher oriented to the building, giving the mentor a tour of the school and to answer any questions s/he has. Additionally, the mentor should explain the school's objectives for student learning i

Teachers and administrators of school sites and units shall jointly plan and participate in staff development on student release days. Site teachers shall be involved in planning and implementing all district staff development activities.

The professional development committee provides guidance and training to help teachers develop communication and collaboration skills to use both in- and outside of the classroom with their colleagues. We encourage our teachers to use technology resources provided by the school and through other venues to collaborate with their peers both in- and outside of Stromburg High School. These resources might include, but are not limited to, e-mail, Internet Resources, on-line training professional development programs, and distance learning professional development programs. Collaboration will help our teachers remain reflective practitioners and abreast of current advances in teaching and learning.\

Stromburg High School wants all new teachers to feel comfortable in both the school and their classrooms; therefore, we have established a mentoring program that relies upon the guidance and knowledge of its many veteran teachers.\\Beginning this year, teachers in their first year of teaching will be assigned to a mentor teacher, who is a more experienced teacher in their particular content area. Mentor Teams will meet once a month after school. The goals of this program are to help new teachers in: 1) curriculum implementation and classroom management, 2) integrating the Literacy Improvement Focus into their unit goals, 3) developing coherent lessons that address national standards in their content area, 4) adjusting to the profession of teaching.\\At the first meeting, the mentor's mission is to get the new teacher oriented to the building, giving the mentor a tour of the school and to answer any questions s/he has. Additionally, the mentor should explain the school's objectives for student learning in the
staff leadership - 60% involved in some form of leadership\\Actions Plans - several teachers helped develop\\broad based committee to design and implement LIF

Stromburg High School has a six- period day. Periods are fifty minutes in length. Period one starts at 8:00 and school dismisses at 2:05 p.m. The teachers' work day is 7:30 to 3:05 p.m.\\    *\\      Most teachers at Stromburg High School teach 5 courses per semester.\    *\\      Most teachers have two classes to prepare for and one planning period per day.\      (A few teachers only have one \prep\" but some have as many as three!)\    *\\      Teachers will usually have at least one meeting per week after school hours.\    *\\      The average number of students taught by each faculty member is around 160."

Faculty meetings occur at 2:15-3:30 p.m. on the third Wednesday of every month. The location is the school cafeteria.\\Topics addressed at meetings include curriculum initiatives, professional development, committee updates, discipline, school policy, state testing, release time, parent involvement, budget, student governance, and special events.\\The principal calls each meeting to order and opens the floor for announcements. To submit items for the meeting, contact Vice Principal Solanus by Friday of the week prior to the meeting.\\All faculty and staff are expected to attend staff meetings. Meetings usually generate lively, focused discussion. Staff members support the democratic process of meetings, engaging in constructive debate and voting for (or against) important items that could impact our school. The Stromburg staff is committed to contributing individual ideas while simultaneously working together to build consensus and a shared vision of the school.\

contract: 7 1/2 day, 1/2 hour duty free lunch\establish school hours 7:30 - 3:05, Mon-Fri\entitled to one prep period\\Professional Development Time\In addition to dates before school and mark reporting days, there may be up to two work days with students released for teacher professional development. Teachers and administrators of school sites and units shall jointly plan and participate in staff development on student release days. Site teachers shall be involved in planning and implementing all district staff development activities.

Part of this year's strategic plan is a Literacy Improvement Focus (LIF). Every content area is to review its standards and look for opportunities to support literacy development in students by emphasizing multiple and varied reading and writing opportunities. For students who have difficulty reading, we are looking into incorporating a program of remediation developed specifically for students in grades 7-12. Stromburg High School wants all new teachers to feel comfortable in both the school and their classrooms; therefore, we have established a mentoring program that relies upon the guidance and knowledge of its many veteran teachers.\\Beginning this year, teachers in their first year of teaching will be assigned to a mentor teacher, who is a more experienced teacher in their particular content area. Mentor Teams will meet once a month after school. The goals of this program are to help new teachers in: 1) curriculum implementation and classroom management, 2) integrating the Literacy Improvement Focus into their unit goals, 3) developing coherent lessons that address national standards in their content area, 4) adjusting to the profession of teaching.\\At the first meeting, the mentor's mission is to get the new teacher oriented to the building, giving the mentor a tour of the school and to answer any questions s/he has. Stromburg High School has a six- period day. Periods are fifty minutes in length. Period one starts at 8:00 and school dismisses at 2:05 p.m. The teachers' work day is 7:30 to 3:05 p.m.\\    *\\      Most teachers at Stromburg High School teach 5 courses per semester.\    *\\      Most teachers have two classes to prepare for and one planning period per day.\      (A few teachers only have one \prep\" but some have as many as three!)\    *\\      Teachers will usually have at least one meeting per week after school hours.\    *\\      The average number of students taught by each faculty member is around 160."

Faculty meetings occur at 2:15-3:30 p.m. on the third Wednesday of every month. The location is the school cafeteria.\\Topics addressed at meetings include curriculum initiatives, professional development, committee updates, discipline, school policy, state testing, release time, parent involvement, budget, student governance, and special events.\\The principal calls each meeting to order and opens the floor for announcements. To submit items for the meeting, contact Vice Principal Solanus by Friday of the week prior to the meeting.\\All faculty and staff are expected to attend staff meetings. Meetings usually generate lively, focused discussion. Staff members support the democratic process of meetings, engaging in constructive debate and voting for (or against) important items that could impact our school. The Stromburg staff is committed to contributing individual ideas while simultaneously working together to build consensus and a shared vision of the school.\

The goals of this program are to help new teachers in: 1) curriculum implementation and classroom management, 2) integrating the Literacy Improvement Focus into their unit goals, 3) developing coherent lessons that address national standards in their content area, 4) adjusting to the profession of teaching.\\At the first meeting, the mentor's mission is to get the new teacher oriented to the building, giving the mentor a tour of the school and to answer any questions s/he has. Faculty meetings occur at 2:15-3:30 p.m. on the third Wednesday of every month. The location is the school cafeteria.\\Topics addressed at meetings include curriculum initiatives, professional development, committee updates, discipline, school policy, state testing, release time, parent involvement, budget, student governance, and special events.\\The principal calls each meeting to order and opens the floor for announcements. To submit items for the meeting, contact Vice Principal Solanus by Friday of the week prior to the meeting.\\All faculty and staff are expected to attend staff meetings. Meetings usually generate lively, focused discussion. Staff members support the democratic process of meetings, engaging in constructive debate and voting for (or against) important items that could impact our school. The Stromburg staff is committed to contributing individual ideas while simultaneously working together to build consensus and a shared vision of the school.\

Tenth Grade English: American Literature and Composition\Although by this age, most students are able to comprehend and learn from their reading, we believe that reading skills still need to be promoted, especially students' motivation to read in areas of interest that influence areas of current and future study. For students who have difficulty reading, we are looking into incorporating a program of remediation developed specifically for students in grades 7-12. Because reading is so important, Stromburg teachers are also examining a variety of methodologies to improve their teaching of reading and are examining more formal formative procedures for evaluating students' in the 9th and 10th grades.

All key stakeholders at a school contribute to the joint development of that school's professional development plan. These stakeholders include the classroom teachers, who share what they consider to be the important focus of curricular needs; the various committees, representing the key components of the school, who share overall assessment of needs; and the local administration, which provide the district with directional information and who allocate the resources and lead the staff forward.

a revitalized professional development program.\\ has created formal guidelines for professional development based on six standards from the National Staff Development Council\\we address the following topics in relation to PROCESSES of professional development \\Data:\Using disaggregated student data to determine adult learning priorities, monitor progress, and help sustain continuous improvement.\\\Evaluation: \Using multiple sources of information to guide improvement and demonstrate its impact. \\\Research:\Preparing educators to apply research to decision making. \\Design: \Using learning strategies appropriate to the intended goal. \\Learning: \Applying knowledge about human learning and change. \\Collaboration \: Providing educators with the knowledge and skills to collaborate

Disaggregated student data will be used to analyze student progress on an annual basis.\\Annual Basis is a problem!\\This information will be used as the basis for monthly meetings of the Professional Development Task Force. Its members include Principal Medina, the professional development coordinator at the district level, and teacher representatives from the various departments (English, Science, Math, Social Studies, etc.). \\\After receiving the mid-year test scores and scores from the NSRE, the principal met with English teachers to analyze data from students' reading and writing scores to speculate why students were performing at such a low level. To make the analysis process more efficient, they utilized software that was available through the district office. This software made the process so efficient, that an overview and report was obtained in two days and was then used to propose changes to the spring semester's curriculum. Plans are being made to provide this software through our school d

Guide and support our teachers and students toward change.\\\For example, we need to know what strategies and resources are available to facilitate a teacher's ability to incorporate new learning practices into their classrooms and how the administration of the school can support teachers in meeting their goals for their own learning and student learning. \\Address adult learning needs and professional goals. \\\For example, we need to make sure that professional development encourages and allows time for teachers to maintain and enhance knowledge about their particular content areas as well as learning and teaching.\\Incorporate teacher knowledge to enhance professional development.\\\The professional development task force plans to assign experienced teachers to use their wealth of practical information about their particular content knowledge and human learning to make changes in Stromburg High School's teacher development practices.\\

This collaboration is done unilatterally??????\\\The professional development committee provides guidance and training to help teachers develop communication and collaboration skills to use both in- and outside of the classroom with their colleagues. We encourage our teachers to use technology resources provided by the school and through other venues to collaborate with their peers both in- and outside of Stromburg High School. These resources might include, but are not limited to, e-mail, Internet Resources, on-line training professional development programs, and distance learning professional development programs. Disaggregated student data will be used to analyze student progress on an annual basis.\\Annual Basis is a problem!\\This information will be used as the basis for monthly meetings of the Professional Development Task Force. Its members include Principal Medina, the professional development coordinator at the district level, and teacher representatives from the various departments (English, Science, Math, Social Studies, etc.). \\\After receiving the mid-year test scores and scores from the NSRE, the principal met with English teachers to analyze data from students' reading and writing scores to speculate why students were performing at such a low level. To make the analysis process more efficient, they utilized software that was available through the district office. This software made the process so efficient, that an overview and report was obtained in two days and was then used to propose changes to the spring semester's curriculum. Plans are being made to provide this software through our school d

Guide and support our teachers and students toward change.\\\For example, we need to know what strategies and resources are available to facilitate a teacher's ability to incorporate new learning practices into their classrooms and how the administration of the school can support teachers in meeting their goals for their own learning and student learning. \\Address adult learning needs and professional goals. \\\For example, we need to make sure that professional development encourages and allows time for teachers to maintain and enhance knowledge about their particular content areas as well as learning and teaching.\\Incorporate teacher knowledge to enhance professional development.\\\The professional development task force plans to assign experienced teachers to use their wealth of practical information about their particular content knowledge and human learning to make changes in Stromburg High School's teacher development practices.\\

Guide and support our teachers and students toward change.\\\For example, we need to know what strategies and resources are available to facilitate a teacher's ability to incorporate new learning practices into their classrooms and how the administration of the school can support teachers in meeting their goals for their own learning and student learning. \\Address adult learning needs and professional goals. \\\For example, we need to make sure that professional development encourages and allows time for teachers to maintain and enhance knowledge about their particular content areas as well as learning and teaching.\\Incorporate teacher knowledge to enhance professional development.\\\The professional development task force plans to assign experienced teachers to use their wealth of practical information about their particular content knowledge and human learning to make changes in Stromburg High School's teacher development practices.\\

Disaggregated student data will be used to analyze student progress on an annual basis.\\Annual Basis is a problem!\\This information will be used as the basis for monthly meetings of the Professional Development Task Force. Its members include Principal Medina, the professional development coordinator at the district level, and teacher representatives from the various departments (English, Science, Math, Social Studies, etc.). \\\After receiving the mid-year test scores and scores from the NSRE, the principal met with English teachers to analyze data from students' reading and writing scores to speculate why students were performing at such a low level. To make the analysis process more efficient, they utilized software that was available through the district office. This software made the process so efficient, that an overview and report was obtained in two days and was then used to propose changes to the spring semester's curriculum. Case Scenario\Imagine that you are a member of the leadership team at Stromburg High School, in an suburban location. Your superintendent has selected your school along with a few others to undertake a comprehensive self-study as a means to improve the educational services of the school. Your leadership team needs to identify a key initiative for the following year that will move your school toward this goal. Your task is to identify the primary issue(s) that need to be addressed and the action steps to take in order to initiate changes of substantial scope that improve the educational experience of students. \

Office for Professional Development and Educational Reform designs ongoing staff development activities for school-based change facilitators and lead teachers. Another major function of this office is to build collaborative networks among school communities, federal agencies, district administrators, and external partners. Through the analysis of feedback data, the office monitors and evaluates the quality of program implementation to adjust/adapt various program components in order to ensure improved instructional delivery and increased student performance. \\\All key stakeholders at a school contribute to the joint development of that school's professional development plan. These stakeholders include the classroom teachers, who share what they consider to be the important focus of curricular needs; the various committees, representing the key components of the school, who share overall assessment of needs; and the local administration, which provide the district with directional information and who allocate

Due to the fact that Stromburg's students have scored low on reading comprehension tests for the past two years, the school adopted a Literacy Improvement Focus (LIF). The tests showed that reading comprehension scores are consistently low across all grade levels; therefore the major goal of the SIP is to support all students in meeting or exceeding performance standards for literacy. Both reading and writing skills need to addressed if reading scores are to increase.\\Preliminary Questions from the LIF:\1. Do all teachers have training in teaching reading comprehension?\\2. Can all teachers implement multiple reading strategies?\\3. How do teachers address different reading levels in their classrooms?\\4. Are reading skills emphasized in all content areas and grade levels?\

column9: School administrators Principal Medina and Vice Principal Solanus chat over coffee in Medina's office before school starts.\\MEDINA: So do you think we are making any progress with the Literacy Improvement Focus? In your classroom observations, have you seen a greater emphasis on writing in classes that have traditionally shunned it?\\SOLANUS: Yes! I know it is hard to believe, given that we have quite a few teachers who are resistant to changing anything, but I think that literacy is such an important and basic issue that everyone is, more or less, trying to work it into their lessons.\\MEDINA: What specifically have you seen?\\SOLANUS: Well, I see science assigning more multi-page reports, with the emphasis on clarity and accuracy. I see quite a few teachers incorporating the Internet, which they say, stimulates students' interest in writing about a content-area topic that interests them. For example, one math teacher assigned a project in which students select a figure from math history and submit a five-p

Classroom-based facilities\\Our classrooms are well lit and ventilated centers for learning. Each classroom has its own computer linked to the Internet for students and teachers to use in accessing information. Now that our teachers have Internet and e-mail, our support staff has been working with them to do on-line collaboration with one another, especially across content areas. In addition, support staff members are working with our teachers to develop on-line assessments of essay-type examinations (one of the elements of the Literacy Improvement Plan). This is a three-step process involving students written essays on-line, teachers writing responses on-line, and students reviewing the comments and responses. Teachers are also beginning to build student portfolios from these essay exams.

Higher Education Involvement\\Your Invitation to a Presentation by Gerry Montgomery, Ph.D, of State University\The university community has expressed an interest in Stromburg High School because we are a culturally diverse community with many talented and motivated teachers and students. They wish to share some of their resources with our school community.\\Gerry Montgomery, a faculty member of the Education Department at State University, will give a talk that describes these resources and how Stromburg High School can take advantage of them. These include, but are not limited to, technology for teachers to use in their classroom as well as to help them develop as professionals, university pre-service teacher mentors for our juniors and seniors, and the opportunity for teachers to collaborate with university faculty to get more information about current teaching and learning strategies in each content area.\\This is the first step in what we hope will be a long-term relationship between Stromburg High School

computer-adaptive testing significantly decreases the time needed to make an accurate assessment. In computer-adaptive testing, the test questions are adapted to the performance level of the test taker, quickly narrowing in on questions that are appropriate to the level of knowledge of the test taker.

Seneca Elementary School's mission is to provide all children with a positive school climate conducive to learning by encouraging good citizenship, good attendance, high scholastic standards, and an awareness and respect for individual differences. \\\\We believe in providing a safe and positive climate for learning in which all students become compassionate, responsible, and contributing members of our diverse community. This mission is accomplished through excellence in teaching and through partnerships with parents and our community.\\

A. Science as inquiry\ 6. Abilities necessary to do scientific inquiry \7. Understanding about scientific inquiry \ \Inquiry is central to science learning. When engaging in inquiry, students describe objects and events, ask questions, construct explanations, test those explanations against current scientific knowledge, and communicate their ideas to others. They identify their assumptions, use critical and logical thinking, and consider alternative explanations. In this way, students actively develop understanding of science by combining scientific knowledge with reasoning and thinking skills.\\

Stromburg High School provides a flexible and varied curriculum that meets the intellectual, social, physical, cultural, technological, and career needs of its students. \\Through cooperative efforts between our staff and the community, we support students' learning and growth both now and in the future.\\\

This school year marks the fourth consecutive year that improvement efforts at Stromburg High School have been guided by our strategic plan. A broad-based committee developed the plan by gathering ideas and input from the entire community, including parents, students, teachers, and administrative staff.\\Our Focus for the Coming Year\\Due to the fact that Stromburg's students have scored low on reading comprehension tests for the past two years, the school adopted a Literacy Improvement Focus (LIF). The tests showed that reading comprehension scores are consistently low across all grade levels; therefore the major goal of the SIP is to support all students in meeting or exceeding performance standards for literacy. Both reading and writing skills need to addressed if reading scores are to increase\\Prelim ?s from LIF:\Follow up as a guideline.

column9: The university community has expressed an interest in Stromburg High School because we are a culturally diverse community with many talented and motivated teachers and students. They wish to share some of their resources with our school community. \\Gerry Montgomery, a faculty member of the Education Department at State University, will give a talk that describes these resources and how Stromburg High School can take advantage of them. These include, but are not limited to, technology for teachers to use in their classroom as well as to help them develop as professionals, university pre-service teacher mentors for our juniors and seniors, and the opportunity for teachers to collaborate with university faculty to get more information about current teaching and learning strategies in each content area.\

I agree with the administration on where they want education to go. I also agree in developing a more systematic and nationally aligned curricula. However, what I resent is the persistence of an old way of structuring the school day that makes it impossible for me to have the time to implement these things well. \\

DOUG: I know. I have been frustrated with the status quo here, and I have thought about applying for a different school in the district. But I have held in here, and I am getting more and more determined to see some changes.\\MATT: I think that Solanus is going to be a real asset. She was brought in to lead the school's reform effort, and I think she is a real leader. Quick to grasp the issues, adept at working with people and getting them to express their thoughts and concerns, and knowledgeable about what needs to be done. I think she understands the complexity of what it takes to improve our student's reading and writing skills. We could not have done much better than her.\\DOUG: I like her too. She brings a fresh perspective and we need that.\\ \

Your Invitation to a Presentation by Gerry Montgomery, Ph.D, of State University\The university community has expressed an interest in Stromburg High School because we are a culturally diverse community with many talented and motivated teachers and students. They wish to share some of their resources with our school community. \\Gerry Montgomery, a faculty member of the Education Department at State University, will give a talk that describes these resources and how Stromburg High School can take advantage of them. These include, but are not limited to, technology for teachers to use in their classroom as well as to help them develop as professionals, university pre-service teacher mentors for our juniors and seniors, and the opportunity for teachers to collaborate with university faculty to get more information about current teaching and learning strategies in each content area.\\This is the first step in what we hope will be a long-term relationship between Stromburg High School and local higher educat
